grep -->  "global regular expression print.â€

grep "error" logfile.txt

grep -i "error" logfile.txt

grep -r "TODO"

grep -n "warning" logfile.txt

grep -c "error" logfile.txt

grep -l "error" *.log --> print only filenames with matches

grep -v "success" logfile.txt --> invert match, find no matching lines

grep "^error" logfile.txt --> match lines starting with a pattern

grep "failure$" logfile.txt  --> match lines ending with a pattern

grep -E "error|failure" logfile.txt  --> E enables extended regular expression

ps aux | grep "firefox"

grep -w "is" file.txt ---> serch for whole words 

grep -irn "error" /var/log  --> combine multi options

find /path/to/dir -name "*.txt" | xargs grep "search_pattern"  --> combine find and grep to search within specific types of files

tail -f /var/log/syslog | grep "ERROR"


Common use cases:
Searching logs: Quickly find error messages or specific events in log files.
Filtering command output: Narrow down results of commands like ps, ls, netstat.
Searching config files: Locate specific configuration settings in large files.
Validating Data: Verify pattern or formats in data files


